<div id="review_1732091350" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1732091350" />
    <a title="Brown Girl Reading" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2682140-brown-girl-reading"><img alt="Brown Girl Reading" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1460474568p2/2682140.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1732091350?book_show_action=true">Aug 24, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brown Girl Reading" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brown Girl Reading" href="/user/show/2682140-brown-girl-reading">Brown Girl Reading</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">literary fiction lovers, short story collections, stories about haitian diaspora</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1732091350" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9631638899647790832">I’d never heard the words Kirk? Krak! and wondered what they meant when I picked this book up. Reading the back cover, I learned that storytellers say Krik? and listeners say Krak! in Haiti. Krik? Krak! is a poetic collection of connected short stories that explores the Haitian community in the United States and in Haiti. <a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='https://browngirlreading.com/2016/08/24/krik-krak/'>https://browngirlreading.com/2016/08/...</a></span>
  <span id="freeText9631638899647790832" style="display:none">I’d never heard the words Kirk? Krak! and wondered what they meant when I picked this book up. Reading the back cover, I learned that storytellers say Krik? and listeners say Krak! in Haiti. Krik? Krak! is a poetic collection of connected short stories that explores the Haitian community in the United States and in Haiti. <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://browngirlreading.com/2016/08/24/krik-krak/">https://browngirlreading.com/2016/08/...</a></span>
