        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1527071254" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11729262026014920592">Let&apos;s start with the opening story, &quot;Children of the Sea.&quot; Imbued with dread, but with the sort of irrational hope that characterizes all wanderers and exiles, it&apos;s something of a wonder. If only the remainder of the book followed up on this promise. The rest of the stories struck me as merely OK, and all too often fell into the oft-repeated, thoroughly marketable tropes of &quot;immigrant family fiction,&quot; (the Rebellious American Daughter, the Betrayal of Communitarian Tradition, etc. etc.). If you&apos;</span>
  <span id="freeText11729262026014920592" style="display:none">Let's start with the opening story, "Children of the Sea." Imbued with dread, but with the sort of irrational hope that characterizes all wanderers and exiles, it's something of a wonder. If only the remainder of the book followed up on this promise. The rest of the stories struck me as merely OK, and all too often fell into the oft-repeated, thoroughly marketable tropes of "immigrant family fiction," (the Rebellious American Daughter, the Betrayal of Communitarian Tradition, etc. etc.). If you're Jhumpa Lahiri, you can get away with this because you're a fucking genius. If you're Edwidge Danticat, and you're merely a perfectly good writer, you need to try a bit harder. </span>
  <a data-text-id="11729262026014920592" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
