<div id="review_1758809086" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1758809086" />
    <a title="Amanda" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7897151-amanda"><img alt="Amanda" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1461450073p2/7897151.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1758809086?book_show_action=true">Aug 01, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Amanda" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Amanda" href="/user/show/7897151-amanda">Amanda</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781616957001" href="/book/show/25739272-krik-krak">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7897151-amanda?shelf=black-literature">black-literature</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7897151-amanda?shelf=short-stories-essays">short-stories-essays</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1758809086" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1191045121594748497">Edwidge Danticat&apos;s Krik? Krak! is a collection of stories about the Haitian experience. We learn about its traumatizing past and how it is viewed by Haitians living in America today. The eleven stories in the 20th anniversary edition bring in elements of folklore and share imagery and sometimes even characters.<br/><br/>As a reader who knows little of Haiti&apos;s history, these stories left me with questions and trepidation about the answers. Many of these stories are haunted by violence and suffering. A youn</span>
  <span id="freeText1191045121594748497" style="display:none">Edwidge Danticat's Krik? Krak! is a collection of stories about the Haitian experience. We learn about its traumatizing past and how it is viewed by Haitians living in America today. The eleven stories in the 20th anniversary edition bring in elements of folklore and share imagery and sometimes even characters.<br /><br />As a reader who knows little of Haiti's history, these stories left me with questions and trepidation about the answers. Many of these stories are haunted by violence and suffering. A young revolutionary is trapped on a slowly sinking boat with other refugees. A bereft woman finds a dead child on the streets and brings her home. A weeping Madonna statue provides the sole comfort for a woman wrongly imprisoned for her ability to fly.<br /><br />There were many powerful images in Krik? Krak!. I find I can remember what happened it each with little difficulty. However, I didn't connect with the characters as much as I had hoped, probably due to my cultural ignorance. I look forward to educating myself about Haitian history and rereading these short stories again.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1191045121594748497" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

